Rethinking the very American ideal of labour rights as human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have introduced a bill to establish the organization of unions as a civil right.
“Just as unions die, so do middle-class jobs,” said Ellison, a Minnesota Democrat and deputy chairman of the Progressive Caucus in Congress.
Therefore, I am proud to present the Employee Empowerment Act together with civil rights icon John Lewis.
This ground-breaking law gives workers the same legal options when it comes to discriminating against trade unions as other forms of discrimination – and thus stops anti-trade union forces.
Complementing the national labour law to create an opportunity for workers exposed to discrimination to organise a trade union representation, to sue a civil court for justice – and to receive compensation or fines – is a sensible and necessary initiative.
But it is certainly not a radical initiative – at least not by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis, and the other sponsors of their bill are proposing is to link back to a very American idea.
Despite the setbacks the unions have faced in recent years – in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states across the country – Americans have once encouraged countries around the world to recognize, expand and uphold labor rights.
There was a time millions of Americans still remember when this country called democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right of association in one breath.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas Mac Arthur and his staff encouraged the country to adopt a constitution designed to ensure that the militarized autocracy of Hedki Tojos would be replaced by democracy.
In full awareness that the workers and their unions took a role in creating a new Japan, they used a language that explicitly recognized that "the rights of the workers to union and joint negotiation and action are guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his staff urged the Germans to write a constitution that would ensure that Adolf Hitler’s fascism would be replaced by a strong democracy.
In recognition of the fact that the workers would have to organize and raise their voice in the new nation, the Germans inserted a clause that explicitly stated: "The right to establish associations to secure and improve working and economic conditions is guaranteed to every individual and every profession or trade.
Agreements that restrict this right or aim to reduce it are null and void; measures aimed at it are unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt presided over the International Human Rights Commission, from which the Universal Declaration of Human Rights was drafted, as it was adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a worldwide agreement, Roosevelt and the other authors added a guarantee that "everyone has the right to protect trade unions."
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When this country advised other countries on how to form civil and democratic societies, Americans declared that the right to form a union - and that this union should then participate in collective bargaining as an equal partner with companies and government agencies - should be protected.
In fact, after these rights have been violated in America, it is very wise to look at the American ideal again, which means that the working population must have the right to unite and to be heard in a free and open society.
As Pastor Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the labor movement did not limit the strength of the nation, but increased it.
By raising the standard of living of millions of people, labor has miraculously created a market for industry and raised the entire nation to unimaginable levels of production.
Those who attack work forget these simple truths, but history preserves them.
History remembers, and so should we.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of civil rights as protection against discrimination in the creation of workers' representatives - has long been overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis renew the ideals that have made America great in the past and fulfilled the promise of democracy.
Judge temporarily halts law that could force all abortion clinics in Louisiana to close
A U.S. federal judge on Sunday temporarily halted the implementation of a law in Louisiana that lawyers say would have led to the closure of all five state abortion clinics.
