Companies in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia collectively paid $27.6 billion to state and local agencies in fiscal 2013, up 3.8 percent from revenue in 2012 of $26.6 billion.
The companies’ state and local tax burden rose 4.3 percent to $671 billion last year, up from 3.9 percent the year before, and it was the third consecutive year of growth after several years of declining 2009 and 2010 rulings.
State taxes rose more than local taxes by 4.3 percent, according to the study conducted by the Ernst & Young Service Agency with the Center for State Taxation, a tax policy group.
More than half of the district’s tax revenue, 56 percent, comes from corporate taxes, while 36 percent of Maryland’s revenue comes from corporations.
Virginia has the lowest corporate income tax rate at 28 percent.
Much of the increase in tax revenue is due to a recovery in companies’ property values, the researchers say, leading to a 3.7 percent increase in property taxes this year after three consecutive years with growth rates of less than 1 percent.
While much of this profit came from large states such as California, New York, and Texas, the process seems to apply to the Washington area as well.
