But the apparent recovery in property values isn’t as effective in raising state and local tax revenues in Maryland, where property taxes account for just over a fifth of corporate tax filings.
Companies in Virginia and D.C. pay nearly half of their state and local taxes in the form of property taxes.
“In Maryland, a large portion of the property, particularly in the tax area around D.C., is either owned by the government or by non-profit organizations that do not pay property taxes,” said Douglas Lindholm, managing director of the Center on State Taxation.
Maryland is therefore forced to rely much more on income taxes, for example, in order to be able to offer the same services that other states offer.
The recent recovery in corporate tax revenues cannot be attributed solely to the recovery of the real estate market.
Corporate revenues also appear to be recovering, according to the data.
Companies in the region reported income taxes on state organizations of $2.3 billion compared to $2.1 billion in 2012.
Maryland took in $1 billion in corporate income taxes, the highest amount in the region.
While the trend is going in the same direction, the local tax burden for businesses does not increase uniformly in all three locations.
The rate of increase in the district was 4.3 percent on the national average, while the increase in Maryland was significantly higher, at 4.9 percent.
Only Virginia reported a lower-than-average tax revenue of 4.1 percent.
Virginia has the lowest corporate income taxes at 6 percent in all three jurisdictions (all three have fixed corporate tax rates).
The corporate tax rate in Maryland is 8.25 percent and in the district at a relatively high 9.975 percent.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year showed that Virginia requires lower state and local corporate taxes and overall a better tax climate than Maryland.
The study did not examine the district.
Despite the benefits, Virginia is under pressure from its southern neighbors.
