Putin calls on Kiev to host “state talks” with eastern Ukraine
Russian President Vladimir Putin demanded on Sunday that the Ukrainian government stop fighting separatists in the east of the country and immediately start negotiations on the "statehood" of the apostate region, according to Russian media reports.
His spokesman Dmitry Peskov later made it clear that Putin did not mean that the separatist-controlled territory of eastern Ukraine would become part of Russia, but that its status vis-<0xC3><0xA0>-vis Ukraine would need to be redefined in order to give the Russian-speaking region the power to represent its rights and interests.
Putin’s call for the Kiev government to negotiate on an equal footing with the pro-Russian insurgents, however, fits with the strategy he apparently pursued since the beginning of the riots five months ago: help for the separatists in taking over territories and pressure on the Ukrainian government to allow the newly proclaimed region of Novorossiysk to become a de facto ally with Russia.
In an interview with state television Channel One, Putin condemned Ukraine’s military campaign to recapture separatist-held areas in the eastern regions of Donetsk and Luhansk, which were captured in March and April after Moscow annexed the Ukrainian peninsula of Crimea on March 18.
The Kremlin and the separatists have recently referred to the occupied territory as "Novorossiya" or "Neurosland", a term reminiscent of the pre-revolutionary heyday of the Russian Empire.
Putin pointed out that all those who, in the course of the campaigns of Ukrainian politicians for the elections on 26 October and while government groups attack civilian communities in the areas held by separatists, hope to be "captured in their illusions", Itar-Tass reported.
"We must immediately enter into detailed discussions, not only on technical issues, but also on the political organization of society and the state status of South-East Ukraine, in order to safeguard the interests of the people living there," he said.
Peskov said Putin’s reference to statehood must be seen in the context of greater autonomy, which has been discussed for months by the Kiev leadership to dispel fears in Russian-speaking areas that their cultural and linguistic rights are at risk.
Only the Ukrainian government can grant the eastern territories the necessary autonomy, Peskov said.
This is not about negotiations between Ukraine and Russia, Peskov said, "because it is not about a conflict between Russia and Ukraine, but about an internal conflict in Ukraine."
The clarification by the Kremlin spokesman to correct the “misinterpretation” of Putin’s remarks underscored Russia’s leadership claim in dealing with the separatist rebellion in the east as opposed to the direct annexation of Crimea, on which the majority of the 2 million inhabitants are ethnic Russians.
Moscow would have far greater difficulty annexing the Donetsk and Luhansk regions in eastern Ukraine, as most of the 6.5 million residents are not Russians, and polls from the time before the conflict showed a broad majority for staying in Ukraine.
The autonomy raised by Russian diplomats on international forums would give the regional governments in Ukraine the power to negotiate their own trade agreements and foreign relations, and thus give the Kremlin de facto control over an area that connects the Russian state with Crimea.
The Black Sea peninsula, which was annexed five months ago, is home to most of the Russian Navy, as well as an important trading port and historic coastal region.
The regions between the Rostov region in Russia and the Crimea are also rich in mines, factories and foundries, which make important components for the Russian military.
Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko, in his inauguration speech on June 7, suggested that Ukrainian legislation should consider additions to the Constitution, which would give the respective territories greater control over their finances and the status of the languages.
But his notion of autonomy seems to stand in stark contrast to those of the Kremlin and the separatist rebels whose weapons and insurgency are being blamed on Moscow.
Putin’s last call to Kiev to negotiate with separatist leaders on a level playing field followed a further push by rebels last week after Russian troops and tanks invaded eastern Ukraine over the previously peaceful region along the Azov Sea.
The Russian-backed separatists seized control of Novoasaovsk, which Ukrainian security officials fear is the first step in a campaign to take over the strategic coastal region as far as Crimea.
For this reason, massive civil and military preparations have begun to consolidate Mariupol, a steel industry port with 500,000 inhabitants, located between Nowoasovsk and the narrow access to the Crimean peninsula.
Poroshenko spoke at an EU leadership meeting in Brussels on Saturday and urged action to prevent further Russian aggression against Ukraine, a former Soviet republic that has been independent for 23 years.
"We are close to a point where there is no going back," Poroshenko warned.
Thousands of foreign troops and hundreds of foreign tanks are now on the territory of Ukraine.
The EU summit did not decide on concrete actions, the leadership demanded the draft of further sanctions against Russia, which should come into force in the event of an unspecified escalation of the Ukraine crisis.
Ukrainian soldiers were forced to withdraw from their positions in Ilovajsk after two Russian tank columns and 1,000 soldiers entered the Donetsk region last week to support the besieged separatists, Colonel Andriy Lysenko, a spokesman for the Ukrainian National Security and Defense Council, said in a report in Kiev on Saturday.
The first alleged 63 Ukrainian soldiers captured by the Russian invasion of Ilovajsk were exchanged on Sunday for 10 Russian paratroopers captured a week ago on Ukrainian territory, Lysenko said.
